  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a broad consensus globally that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. This practice is universally recognized as illegal because it enables criminals to disguise the proceeds of their illicit activities, thereby undermining the integrity of financial systems and facilitating further criminal behavior.\n\nAlmost all countries have established legal frameworks to combat money laundering. These include laws that criminalize the act of money laundering itself, as well as regulations that require financial institutions to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities. International organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), set global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts and promote the implementation of these standards across jurisdictions.\n\nKey components of anti-money laundering laws typically include:\n\n1. **Criminalization of Money Laundering**: Making it a crime to knowingly engage in transactions involving proceeds of criminal activity.\n2. **Customer Due Diligence (CDD)**: Requiring financial institutions to verify the identity of their customers and understand the nature of their activities.\n3. **Reporting Suspicious Activities**: Mandating that financial institutions report transactions that they suspect may be related to money laundering or other criminal activities.\n4. **Record-Keeping**: Requiring financial institutions to maintain records of transactions for a specified period to assist in investigations.\n5. **International Cooperation**: Facilitating the sharing of information and collaboration between countries to combat cross-border money laundering.\n\nGiven the widespread recognition of the harm caused by money laundering, there is strong international cooperation and consensus on the need to enforce anti-money laundering laws rigorously.",
